234
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:36,000
We want Lithos to be scalable.

235
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,000
We want it to be able to potentially
handle hundreds of thousands of miners at

236
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:42,000
once.

237
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:51,000
And past solutions to decentralized
mining haven't been able to do that.

238
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:54,000
So the first technical aspect, and I've
talked about it recently, is

239
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:57,000
collateralized mining pools.

240
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,000
And we want collateralization to
essentially ensure that block production

241
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,000
is in the hands of miners.

242
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:06,000
We want miners to gain MEV rewards.

243
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:10,000
We want miners to be able to have control
over their storage rent.

244
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:18,000
We want to avoid censorship of any
transactions at all.

245
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:22,000
And another technical aspect here is the
non-interactive share proof, which is

246
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:26,000
really, I think the most important part of
Lithos and it completely changes how

247
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:30,000
mining is done.

248
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:35,000
Mining, traditionally, on a mining pool,
you get your mining software, you connect

249
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,000
to the stratum, and you produce hundreds
of thousands of shares over a period of

250
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:43,000
time.

251
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:48,000
The mining pool takes these shares, they
store in the database, and they determine

252
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:52,000
how much work you did by looking at the
amount of shares multiplied by the

253
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:56,000
difficulty that you mined at.

254
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:03,000
And obviously, this is not good enough
for a smart contract.

255
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:06,000
It just takes too much space and
computation.

256
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:10,000
So NISPs are the alternative.

257
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:14,000
And they ask sort of a different question
of the miner.

258
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:20,000
Instead of asking how many shares did you
produce over a period of time, we're

259
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:26,000
asking, can you produce, say, 10 shares at
a high enough difficulty to prove that you

260
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:32,000
did a certain amount of work while the
block solution was being generated.

261
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:37,000
And this kind of change of the question
has a big implication in terms of how

262
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:41,000
mining works on Lithos.

263
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:45,000
You're not going to be mining in the
traditional way.

264
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:48,000
Obviously, you'll still have a mining
software, you'll still have a stratum that

265
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
you connect to, but the way your rewards
are calculated are completely different.

266
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:56,000
You are not simply adding up the number
of shares and then dividing it based on

267
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,000
the total number of shares produced by the
pool.

268
00:22:01,000 --> 00:22:05,000
You are essentially proving that you did
a certain amount of work by producing

269
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:09,000
these high value shares.

270
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:19,000
And then that allows you to store all
this data in a small space.

271
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:23,000
NISPs also are very important because
they are computationally efficient and

272
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:27,000
they're efficient storage-wise.

273
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:31,000
We can use optimistic roll-ups to allow
for greater scalability with the smart

274
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,000
contracts that we're using.

275
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:41,000
Now, an optimistic roll-up, you can think
of it as a layer two solution that is

276
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:47,000
essentially it's taking all these NISPs
and it's assuming that each NISP is going

277
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:53,000
to be completely successful and valid.

278
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:56,000
Unless it is checked upon.

279
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:00,000
Now, in Lithos, we plan to have lots of
off-chain bots that will be checking each

280
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,000
NISP submitted to the blockchain.

281
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:10,000
And if a NISP is found to be fraudulent,
a fraud-proof transaction is submitted,

282
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:16,000
and that NISP is removed from the
equation.

283
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:19,000
This is really important because we're
not evaluating each share proof on its

284
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:22,000
own.

285
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:27,000
We're only evaluating share proofs when
we know they're fraudulent.

286
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:32,000
And what I mean by that is we're not
evaluating share proofs on the blockchain.

287
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:36,000
Obviously, evaluation is happening
off-chain, but we're really focused on

288
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:40,000
on-chain evaluation because that is what
is costly.

289
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:47,000
And fraud proofs allow for us to minimize
the amount of computation on-chain while

290
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:54,000
allowing the majority of computation to
happen off-chain, where computation is

291
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:01,000
easy to do and there are way less limits
regarding data and space.

292
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:06,000
There will be incentive to submit fraud
proofs.

293
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:11,000
Now, usually with roll-ups, we have what
